Sediment_Collection_Depth_cm: 1-3 cm as described in the protocol
MiniDot_Notes: river stage/flow is visibly higher than initial visit. Visible white bubbles on surface flow. Weather is similar to the initial visit (80s and sunny, light wind).
Additional_Sampling_Notes: Sediment substrate surface very rich in dark green algae, with sandy textured material below algal/organic rich layer. Reach where sampling took place is effectively a partially natural flood conveyance channel: shallow sediment overlying concrete, pervasive rubbly material (cobble to boulder sized) placed across stream (see photos). Stream banks are natural sediment (as in CM_008-exposed photo) but inset within a large levee made of rip-rap and concrete. Upstream of site (~800m at Hellman Rd crossing), the stream is a flood conveyance channel lined 100% with concrete. Additionally, looks like some flow is siphoned off immediately upstream of sampling site (just below Hellman Rd crossing) to Mill Creek Wetlands as a form of stormwater/irrigation runoff treatment.
Hydrograph_Online: https://waterdata.usgs.gov/nwis/uv?site_no=11073495  [USGS gauge located a few kilometers upstream of site, but likely representative]

Sediment_Collection_Depth_cm: 1-3 cm as described in the protocol
Additional_Sampling_Notes: Water was slightly turbid (65.3 NTU), our ProDSS measured 109.7 % sat and 9.10 mg/L DO at start of minidot deployment. Specific Conductivity was 412.2 uS/cm. The filtered water bottle had ~100mL of unfiltered water in it, we went through all the filters.  The sieving was taking too long, so we started to pick out the large bits by hand (mostly snail shells).  Not all the photos fit, here's a link for more: https://www.dropbox.com/sh/386901lt9ci5plt/AAD9jwSM-Lycc65zSz11YRLAa?dl=0. We have 47 years of data from this location- nutrients and TSS.  There's a sonde deployed as well, if you need any diel DO or other details.

Sediment_Collection_Depth_cm: 1-3 cm as described in the protocol
MiniDot_Notes: Sensor was 1 m from "depositional bank" ( = sand, gravel over bedrock that has a stagnant, shallow water pool between it and the "real" bank of the river.). The sensor was about 5 m from the "real" bank at that point in time. We took water samples within 10 m down the river from the sensor because the river sediment was so fine that sampling disturbed sediment so that it may have interfered with the sensor readings.
Additional_Sampling_Notes: - Samples packed in ice 5:00 - 5:15  pm on 1/17/23 and driven to FedEx with a 5:45 pm pick up for overnight packages. Expected delivery at PNNL before 4 pm on 1/18/23. Tracking info: https://www.fedex.com/fedextrack/?trknbr=817383356941&trkqual=2459962000~817383356941~FX. Site weather = Sunny, 22C. I provided a diagram (sketch) of the site with estimated distances in the uploaded files section in this form.The bank was level with fine and course sediments - if vegetation was present it was grasses on the bank (grasses appeared to be some Phragmites sp. and/or Paspalum denticulatum). There was a steep incline up to a terrace (but it was not more than 4 m long) and the terrace was vegetated with hardwoods (dominated by Platanus occidentalis). Most importantly, there was a dry, ephemeral tributary at the "real" bank (see sensor notes above)nearest to area we sampled. There was evidence of erosional deposition present. The source of the ravine/tributary was a bare/muddy watering area of a densely populated cattle ranch. The river sediment was so fine that getting it through the filters was incredibly difficult (especially when using a 50 ml syringe) and therefore we used many filters. It would have been easier to use smaller syringes, but trying to fill a 500 ml bottle with a small syringe would have been tedious). Therefore the "filtered water" sample (BWT - filtered) had to be filled with non-filtered water. We managed to fill it to nearly 150 ml of filtered water, but it took 30 mins and we couldn't do that 3-4 more times. Therefore, we filled the remaining 400 ml with unfiltered water. Unfiltered noted on bottle. The unfiltered bottle (BWT) is only 50% filled due to the cap not being screwed on enough during transport to lab. All vials/bottles were individually wrapped and so the water did not contaminate other samples in the cooler. Apologies - we had a team of 5 doing the sampling (and it took 2 hours). Collection photo - difficult to get 1 m2 since the whole team is super short.

Tracking info: https://www.fedex.com/fedextrack/?trknbr=817383356941&trkqual=2459962000~817383356941~FX. Site weather = Sunny, 22C. I provided a diagram (sketch) of the site with estimated distances in the uploaded files section in this form.The bank was level with fine and course sediments - if vegetation was present it was grasses on the bank (grasses appeared to be some Phragmites sp. and/or Paspalum denticulatum). There was a steep incline up to a terrace (but it was not more than 4 m long) and the terrace was vegetated with hardwoods (dominated by Platanus occidentalis). Most importantly, there was a dry, ephemeral tributary at the "real" bank (see sensor notes above)nearest to area we sampled. There was evidence of erosional deposition present. The source of the ravine/tributary was a bare/muddy watering area of a densely populated cattle ranch. The river sediment was so fine that getting it through the filters was incredibly difficult (especially when using a 50 ml syringe) and therefore we used many filters. It would have been easier to use smaller syringes, but trying to fill a 500 ml bottle with a small syringe would have been tedious). Therefore the "filtered water" sample (BWT - filtered) had to be filled with non-filtered water. We managed to fill it to nearly 150 ml of filtered water, but it took 30 mins and we couldn't do that 3-4 more times. Therefore, we filled the remaining 400 ml with unfiltered water. Unfiltered noted on bottle. The unfiltered bottle (BWT) is only 50% filled due to the cap not being screwed on enough during transport to lab. All vials/bottles were individually wrapped and so the water did not contaminate other samples in the cooler. Apologies - we had a team of 5 doing the sampling (and it took 2 hours). Collection photo - difficult to get 1 m2 since the whole team is super short.

Right before shipping (taking out of the refrigerator), frost was observed on ziploc bags and bulk water samples felt frozen in their bottles.

Sediment_Collection_Depth_cm: 1-3 cm as described in the protocol
MiniDot_Notes: The sensor was deployed about 165 cm below water surface
Additional_Sampling_Notes: The sampling site is a boat ramp, but water there is very muddy. We thus sampled water from a fishing deck several feet south to the boat ramp. The water at the fishing deck was very deep, and water was full of sediments. We had to replace a filter for every two syringes of water. Because water was deep at the fishing dock, we took sediment samples at the boat ramp, where the sediment is mainly gravel. It took us a long time to filter fine sands for sampling. Due to the muddy river water and gravel sediments, it thus took us about 2.5 hours to finish the sampling. On the date (5/22/2023) of sampling, it rained heavily in Blountstown and Tallahassee upstream of the sampling site.

River_Gradient: Relatively steep gradient (e.g., mountainous or hilly terrain)
Sediment_Collection_Depth_cm: 3-10cm in some places
MiniDot_Notes: Due to water being so shallow, sensor had to be in contact with riverbed. However, I slightly elevated the inlet with some cobbles.
Additional_Sampling_Notes: It was getting dark when we were doing the sediment sampling, so we were not able to fill up the bottle up to the neck. Hopefully this won't be too detrimental. Additionally, temperature data was obtained through sensors deployed further upstream (where I have the sampling equipment for my research), hopefully the discrepancy in measured temperature isn't much of an issue. The difference in temperature at both locations shouldn't be too much since they are only ~60m apart from each other. I had to dig further into the streambed to obtain the sediment, since there weren't a lot of depositional zones. I do not think I exceeded 10 cm though.

I did not transfer any of the labels from the original 60ml glass amber vial or the filter but have sent them back in the shipment- labeled as contaminated. The thermometers that I brought sampling were for taking human's temperature and could not register the stream water temperature.

Sediment_Collection_Depth_cm: 1-3 cm as described in the protocol
Additional_Sampling_Notes: Lost chamber, swept away by river when no one was looking. Extra minidot and new bottle were used next day. Manual chamber data post-processing notes: initial QAQC plots using metadata incubation start/end times indicate that the incubation period was only 15 mins instead 75 mins for both miniDOT (SNs 412314 and 255981; one miniDOT was swept away). Upon review of the data, photos, etc., we determined that the incubation end time was probably manually recorded in PDT as opposed to PST. We added 60 mins to the incubation period and replotted the data, which showed that there was 75 mins of data. SGF edited the metadata fields "Manual_Chamber_Incubation_End_Time_PST" and Manual_Chamber_Time_Turned_Off_PST" to add 60 mins,  changing the times from 15:08 to 16:08 to reflect the actual data. (3/1/2023 BF) We suspect the end time for the manta was also written in PDT instead of PST. 60 minutes was also added to "Manta_End_Time_PST" and "Manta_Time_Turned_Off_PST"

Manual chamber data post-processing notes: initial QAQC plots using metadata incubation start/end times indicate that the incubation period was only 16 mins instead 75 mins for both miniDOT (SNs 856289, 186138, and 718459). Upon review of the data, photos, etc., we determined that the incubation end time was probably manually recorded in DST as opposed to PST. We added 60 mins to the incubation period and replotted the data, which showed that there was 75 mins of data. SGF edited the metadata fields "Manual_Chamber_Incubation_End_Time_PST" and Manual_Chamber_Time_Turned_Off_PST" to add 60 mins, changing the times from 13:10 to 14:10 to reflect the actual data.

General_Vegetation: Broadleaf evergreen tree. Broadleaf deciduous tree
Additional_Sampling_Notes: For access reasons we sampled 3 km from the USGS gauging station. I have extensive experience working in the upper 20 km of the Lower Colorado downstream from Longhorn Dam. and can confirm that the conditions at our sampling site are representative of the river conditions near the USGS gauge. There are no major inflows between the sampling site and the USGS gauge so river conditions at the gauge are also representative of conditions at the sampling site.

Canopy_Cover: No or almost no direct sunlight (>80% canopy cover)
Additional_Sampling_Notes: My assistant accidentally opened the non-acidified amber vial for 2 seconds. She did not touch the septum. We proceeded to fill the vial and send it with the other samples. We were able to fill all replicate samples and were still able to push another 720 ml of water through the filter. We could have pushed another 60-120 ml through (maybe moreWHON). I hope we captured enough microbial biomass. Our downstream site was below the USGS gage. while the mid and upstream sites were above the USGS gage.

River_Gradient: Relatively steep gradient (e.g., mountainous or hilly terrain)
Additional_Sampling_Notes: In addition to grass & broadleaf deciduous trees. there are many large shrubs/bushes on edges of stream channel. Upstream and Midstream samples were taken upstream of the gauging station (weir). downstream site is located downstream of the weir. Cows have access to the stream. The height of the water column is reported as the height where sediment is collected. Depth of the river at the deepest point in the cross-section at these locations is ~25cm.
